	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nrcQxOyEBTeTCAEYF",
			"markdown": "Rogues survive on adaptability, nerve, and a willingness to operate outside the boundaries of respectable society. Thieves, smugglers, pirates, grifters, hustlers, fences, black marketeers, infiltrators, scavengers, and street survivors all fall under this template. Rogues rely on stealth, deception, improvisation, and social awareness to exploit opportunities, escape danger, and stay one step ahead of the people trying to control them.\n\nThe Rogue is intentionally broad and flexible. Its skills represent survival and influence within informal systems of power: criminal networks, underground economies, frontier settlements, pirate crews, corrupt bureaucracies, and desperate communities where official authority is weak, hostile, or easily manipulated. Some Rogues are subtle infiltrators or manipulators, while others are fast-talking operators, hardened street predators, or charming scoundrels. In many campaigns, the Rogue serves as the party’s fixer, infiltrator, scout, negotiator, fence, smuggler, or underworld contact, solving problems through cunning, preparation, and audacity rather than direct force.\n\nThe *Burglar* is the classic cat burglar, infiltrator, tomb robber, second-story thief, or covert break-in specialist. Burglar builds excel at bypassing security, entering forbidden places, and escaping before anyone realizes they were there. They focus on Stealth, Lockpicking, Climbing, Search, Observation, Escape, Holdout, Traps, and Electronics Operation (Security), supported by Flexibility, Perfect Balance, Silence, Daredevil, and Night Vision. Many Burglars are driven by Greed, Curiousity, Kleptomania, or simple Overconfidence in their ability to get in and out unseen.\n\nThe *Con Artist* covers confidence artists, gamblers, seducers, propagandists, fake mystics, and professional manipulators. Some Con Artists rely on charm and likability, while others weaponize intimidation, sympathy, or carefully crafted false identities. They emphasize Acting, Fast-Talk, Sex Appeal, Public Speaking, Fortune-Telling, Gambling, Psychology, and Savoir-Faire, backed by Smooth Operator, Voice, Charisma, Honest Face, and Social Chameleon. Their lifestyles often encourage disadvantages such as Compulsive Lying, Lecherousness, Trickster, Greed, or Overconfidence.\n\nThe *Freebooter* fits blockade runners, black-market couriers, pirates, fence operators, gunrunners, and illicit traders. Freebooters thrive in dangerous borderlands, criminal ports, and places where legal commerce cannot meet demand. They specialize in Smuggling, Merchant, Streetwise, Holdout, Area Knowledge, Navigation, Piloting, Electronics Operation (Security), and combat sidearms, supported by Contacts, Patron, Cultural Adaptability, Luck, and Daredevil. Many Freebooters develop Greed, Enemies, or a Code of Honor tied to crew loyalty, criminal professionalism, or pirate traditions.\n\nThe *Enforcer* is the gang lieutenant, bounty hunter, urban survivor, debt collector, criminal fixer, or street-level tough who keeps order through intimidation and violence. Enforcers survive through toughness, instinct, and an intimate understanding of how power works at ground level. They focus on Streetwise, Intimidation, Fast-Talk, Observation, Shadowing, Search, Scrounging, and combat skills, paired with Tough Guy, Combat Reflexes, High Pain Threshold, Fearlessness, and Reputation. Their harsh environments often produce disadvantages such as Bad Temper, Bully, Bloodlust, Callous, or a fierce Sense of Duty toward a gang, neighborhood, or crew.\n\nThe *Ghost* covers covert infiltrators, elite pickpockets, espionage thieves, surveillance specialists, and near-supernatural stealth experts. Ghosts avoid fair confrontations whenever possible, preferring patience, positioning, and invisibility over open conflict. They emphasize Stealth, Shadowing, Holdout, Observation, Disguise, Escape, Electronics Operation (Surveillance), Electronics Operation (Security), and Sleight of Hand, supported by Silence, Peripheral Vision, Intuition, Absolute Timing, and Flexibility. The isolation and paranoia of this lifestyle often lead to disadvantages such as Loner, Paranoia, Secret Identity, Obsession, or Workaholic.\n\nRogues should think carefully about how they relate to society and authority. Some are selfish predators or career criminals, while others are rebels, folk heroes, reluctant outcasts, or practical survivors forced into gray areas by circumstance. Even highly combat-capable Rogues generally avoid prolonged stand-up fights, preferring escape routes, surprise, leverage, and unfair advantages whenever possible."
		}
	]
